&gt;&gt; --- In cantera@yahoogroups.com, David Goodwin &lt;dgoodwin@c...&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt;&gt; Michael,
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; Cantera flags some reactions as duplicatess that Chemkin does not.
&gt;&gt; All
&gt;&gt;&gt; you have to do is tell Cantera that you intend this by adding:
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; options = &quot;duplicate&quot;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; for each reaction it flags as an undeclared duplicate, for example:
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; falloff_reaction( &quot;h + o2 (+ M) &lt;=&gt; ho2 (+ M)&quot;
&gt;&gt;&gt;           kf = [4.52000E+013, 0, 0],
&gt;&gt;&gt;           kf0   = [1.05000E+019, -1.257, 0],
&gt;&gt;&gt;           efficiencies = &quot; ch4:10  co:1.9  co2:3.8  h2:0  h2o:0
&gt;&gt; n2:0 &quot;,
&gt;&gt;&gt;           options = &quot;duplicate&quot;)
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; This is done intentionallly, since a reaction like h + o2 (+ n2)
&gt;&gt; &lt;=&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; ho2 (+ n2) could also be written as h + o2 (+ M) &lt;=&gt; ho2 (+ M) with
&gt;&gt; all
&gt;&gt;&gt; efficiencies set to zero except the one for n2.
&gt;&gt;&gt; Also, if you have two reactions
&gt;&gt;&gt;   A + B &lt;=&gt; C + D
&gt;&gt;&gt; and
&gt;&gt;&gt; C + D &lt;=&gt; A + B
&gt;&gt;&gt; Cantera says these are duplicates, but Chemkin does not.
&gt;&gt;&gt; Cantera performs some other checks too, such as whether NASA
&gt;&gt; polynomial
&gt;&gt;&gt; thermo parameterizations are continuous at the midpoint
&gt;&gt; temperature,
&gt;&gt;&gt; etc.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; These extra checks can help find error in reaction mechanisms that
&gt;&gt;&gt; might otherwise go unnoticed, which is especially a problem with
&gt;&gt; very
&gt;&gt;&gt; large mechanisms.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt; Dave
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;&gt;
